post_text: Football season is underway, but it's going to look a bit different tonight. Please remember that for the month of August there are NO spectators admitted to games (for ALL sports). This includes attempting to watch from the parking lot or lining up along fences. Please respect these procedures so we can continue to allow our athletes to play their sports. We look forward to the day when fans can return. In the meantime, you can watch many games at www.ihsaatv.org. #INthistogether #ReturntoPlay #GoArchers #GoBruins #GoGenerals #GoLegends #GoPanthers

post_text:
Families who did not register online will need to register in a drive-thru registration at their child’s school July 23, 24 or 27. This option is being made available for those not able to complete registration online.

Those attending the drive-thru registration will need to bring photo identification and two proofs of residency (utility bill, bank statement, mortgage or rental papers, etc.). New students will also need proof of age, such as a birth certificate, and immunization records.

Drive-thru school registrations will take place:

Thursday, July 23, 2-6 p.m.
Friday, July 24, 8 a.m.-noon
Monday, July 27, 8 a.m.-noon

post_text: Want to serve on the FWCS Board of School Trustees? The Board is seeking applicants for the District 4 seat previously held since 2011 by Jordan Lebamoff, who passed away in March. Written applications must be submitted by June 30, 2020, answering two questions: 1. What qualifications, background and skills would you bring to assist the Board in reaching the District’s Mission and Vision; 2. What knowledge/experience do you have with FWCS? Applicants must have at least one year of residency within District 4, be at least 21 years old and be a registered voter. A map of precincts included in District 4 can be found at fwcs.info/DistrictMap and http://www.allencounty.us/images/election_board/pdfs/districts/Fort_Wayne_Community_Schools_Districts.pdf.

post_text: Thank you to the The City of Fort Wayne for supporting out seniors!
shared_text:
Riverfront Fort Wayne was sharing a COVID-19 Update.
May 13 at 11:51 AM ·

To show support and to honor 2020 high school graduates, the The City of Fort Wayne will light the Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. Bridge in Downtown Fort Wayne. On Thursday, Mayor Tom Henry announced that each Fort Wayne and Allen County high school will have their school’s colors represented on the MLK Bridge May 16-21, 2020. Beginning at dusk each evening, lighting on the bridge will transition between the colors of all 18 local high schools.

“Graduating high school is a once-in-a-lifetime experience. It’s unfortunate that many of our high school seniors will not celebrate their accomplishments due to the COVID-19 situation,” said Mayor Henry. “As a community, we want to show support to our graduating seniors by recognizing their hard work and achievements. I offer my sincerest congratulations to all of the 2020 high school graduates.”

Students and families are encouraged to take photos of the MLK Bridge and share them on social media. The public is reminded to practice social distancing and take precautionary safety measures.

To show support and to honor 2020 high school graduates, the The City of Fort Wayne will light the Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. Bridge in Downtown Fort Wayne. On Thursday, Mayor Tom Henry announced that each Fort Wayne and Allen County high school will have their school’s colors represented on the MLK Bridge May 16-21, 2020. Beginning at dusk each evening, lighting on the bridge will transition between the colors of all 18 local high schools.

“Graduating high school is a once-in-a-lifetime experience. It’s unfortunate that many of our high school seniors will not celebrate their accomplishments due to the COVID-19 situation,” said Mayor Henry. “As a community, we want to show support to our graduating seniors by recognizing their hard work and achievements. I offer my sincerest congratulations to all of the 2020 high school graduates.”

Students and families are encouraged to take photos of the MLK Bridge and share them on social media. The public is reminded to practice social distancing and take precautionary safety measures.

shared_text:
EMS LINQ
April 30 at 1:15 PM ·

Our District of the Week is Fort Wayne Community Schools for their hard work feeding their community! Candice Hagar, Director of Food Services and her team are serving breakfast and lunch to all children under 18 regardless of whether or not they are students of the district. The district is set up at each of their thirty elementary school sites on a daily basis, distributing one breakfast and one lunch for each child that is present in the “drive-thru." Thank you, Candice and team, for your continued hard work!

Know a #schoollunchhero or other school administrator going above and beyond for their students while school is closed? Tell us their story by tagging us and using #LINQStrong and we'll feature them as our District of the Week!

post_text:
Fort Wayne Community Schools has canceled most events and all field trips until further notice in an effort to follow the guidance of health experts to limit large gatherings to slow the spread of COVID-19. The pre-K and kindergarten registration events scheduled for later this month have been postponed until further notice.
Schools will inform families of specific events to be canceled, but the cancellations would include carnivals, concerts, assemblies and other large gatherings. Decisions on sporting events are still being made on connection with IHSAA. In cases where parents paid in advance for field trips or out-of-state trips, schools are working to obtain reimbursements.
In addition, volunteers and consultants who work with the schools are being asked to stay out of school buildings for the time-being.
text:
Fort Wayne Community Schools has canceled most events and all field trips until further notice in an effort to follow the guidance of health experts to limit large gatherings to slow the spread of COVID-19. The pre-K and kindergarten registration events scheduled for later this month have been postponed until further notice.
Schools will inform families of specific events to be canceled, but the cancellations would include carnivals, concerts, assemblies and other large gatherings. Decisions on sporting events are still being made on connection with IHSAA. In cases where parents paid in advance for field trips or out-of-state trips, schools are working to obtain reimbursements.
In addition, volunteers and consultants who work with the schools are being asked to stay out of school buildings for the time-being.

post_text: We are saddened by the death of Fort Wayne Community Schools Board Member Jordan Lebamoff. Jordan was first elected to represent the Fourth District on the FWCS Board of School Trustees in 2011. He was proud to represent the District where his family has lived for generations, as well as his alma mater. Jordan was a 1984 graduate of South Side High School. He chose to raise his two sons, Sebastien and Julien, with his wife, Nicole, within view of South Side in the house his grandfather built and where he and his father were raised. He was committed to improving the neighborhood around South Side as a property owner and landlord. Jordan was an advocate for all students, just as he was for his own sons, and his presence on the Board and in the community will be missed. Our condolences go out to his family.

post_text: Every 10 years, the U.S. Census Bureau undertakes a mammoth task: counting all the people residing in the United States. This count affects the allocation of funding for our community’s public resources (e.g., roads, hospitals, schools), how we plan for the future, and our voice in government. Learn more about the importance of the #2020Census and how to participate: 2020census.gov.
